The two Poles
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to strip Bronislaw Geremek of his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner and former Foreign Affairs Minister - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another statement claiming he was not a secret police agent during the communist era.
European parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's behavior and Geremek stated that the law on decommunization constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of inciting anti-Polish sentiment.
Communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional tribunal decision on May 11 largely invalidated the lustration law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law fits within the general policy of the Polish government, which has only one goal: to weaken the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first, a struggle for freedom, then a struggle for power.
The first is a liberation of the human soul through which man expresses his best qualities, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish trade union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into secrecy when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reappear in the open in 1989, in the wake of the "perestroïka" initiated by Gorbachev.
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship throughout the Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than revenge, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes of government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and of the market economy.
But not everyone has followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-minded groups, post-communist provincial troublemakers, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the voice of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
One sees everywhere worrying signs: the authority of the judiciary is undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Tribunal is questioned, officials are bought, and the role of prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all of this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and its losers.
The Polish revolution brought about public freedoms, but also increased crime, a market economy but also the risk of business failure and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a growing income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also caused fear of the foreign and fear of an invasion of mass Western culture.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers have become the victims of the freedoms they have won.
In the communist prison universe, people were considered belonging to the State, but the latter took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the ruling coalition governs, combining George Bush's conservative potion with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
Solidarity veterans thought that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the heavens.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished and the virtuous activists of Solidarity were not rewarded.
Thus, the feeling of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed both against former enemies and old friends who seemed to be getting away with it.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was the greatest success of Poland in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland was in need of a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes would not go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be corrected.
After their victory in the general elections of 2005, the political parties of the losers chose a method: a large purge.
According to the first estimates, the cleansing process should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people promised to the cleansing must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and banned from practicing their profession for ten years.

The cardinal Dziwisz of Cracow reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, disrespect for human dignity, and baseless accusations".
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this purge have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not the hunt for suspects, whether proven or not, who had belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had taken place in 1990, neither the economic reforms of Leszek Balcerowicz nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO, nor of the European Union.
Today, two Poles are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and vengeance is fighting the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland - made of openness and tolerance, the one of John Paul II and Czeslaw Milisz, of my friends from the underground and from prison - must prevail.
I believe that the Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The decision of the constitutional tribunal leaves hope that the second phase of the Polish revolution will not destroy either what gave it birth, the desire for freedom, or what it has generated, a democratic state.
